			<div type="apparatus">
				<listApp/>
			</div>
			<div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
				<p><!--english translation here--></p>
				<!-- MM: initially tempted to gloss as 'POSS I': 'mine'? if we assume ṅa is 'I' as in Tibetan, Burmese, Tangut, and Chinese; gay·ṁḥ might then be a royal 'we' and/or an unrelated grammaticalized noun. But °o marks the possessed, not the possessor, so if ṅa is 'I', then this is saying 'I' belong to someone - and why would that be on a brick? Unless the 'I' refers to the brick and this is a gag of some sort. Also possible that °o is a nominalizer and ṅa is a verb; Old Chinese *sŋa 'revive' comes to mind, but a cognate would not make sense in this context. Lastly, maybe ṅa is a short form of 'five' after °o. Cf. plaṁ 'four' on 150. What would we expect on bricks? What has been written on SE Asian bricks in other languages? -->
			</div>
			<div type="commentary">
				<p><!-- commentary --></p>
			</div>
